  "datePublished": "2026-01-01",
  "description": "A prior is a probability distribution that represents what you believe about a hypothesis before seeing any evidence. It is the starting point of Bayesian inference — the baseline against which new data are weighed. If you are estimating the bias of a coin, the prior encodes your initial uncertainty: maybe you believe the coin is probably fair (prior concentrated near p=0.5p = 0.5), or maybe you know nothing and consider all values equally plausible (uniform prior over [0,1][0, 1]).\n",
  "name": "Prior",
